{{Orphan|date=April 2011}}

'''Elitzur's theorem''' is a [[theorem]] in [[Quantum field theory|quantum]] and [[statistical field theory]] stating that local [[Gauge theory|gauge symmetries]] cannot be [[Spontaneous symmetry breaking|spontaneously broken]]. The theorem was proposed in 1975 by [[Shmuel Elitzur]], who proved it for [[Abelian group|Abelian]] gauge fields on a [[Lattice gauge theory|lattice]].<ref>{{cite journal | author = Elitzur S | year = 1975 | title = Impossibility of spontaneously breaking local symmetries | journal = Phys. Rev. D | volume = 12 | pages = 3978–3982 | doi = 10.1103/PhysRevD.12.3978|bibcode = 1975PhRvD..12.3978E }}</ref> It is nonetheless possible to spontaneously break a global symmetry within a theory that has a local gauge symmetry, as in the [[Higgs mechanism]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2015}}

