'''Mathematical physiology''' is an [[interdisciplinarity|interdisciplinary science]]. Primarily, it investigates ways in which [[mathematics]] may be used to give insight into [[physiology|physiological]] questions. In turn, it also describes how physiological questions can lead to new mathematical problems. The field may be broadly grouped into two physiological application areas: [[cell (biology)|cell physiology]] – including mathematical treatments of [[biochemistry|biochemical reactions]], [[ion channel|ionic flow]] and [[regulation of gene expression|regulation of function]] – and [[biological system|systems physiology]] – including [[electrophysiology|electrocardiology]], [[circulatory system|circulation]] and [[digestion]].<ref>{{cite web |url = https://people.maths.ox.ac.uk/fowler/courses/physiol/physiolnotes.pdf |title = An Introduction to Mathematical Physiology |last1=Chapman |first1 = S. Jon |last2 = Fowler |first2 = Andrew |last3 = Hinch |first3 = Rob |date = 18 January 2006 |work = University of Oxford |location = Oxford}}</ref>

